relevant_communication:
1.    Ethical trade programmes:  
o    Bangladesh: we have established a local ethical trade platform where our current programme is reaching 54,000 workers in more than 25 factories. ETI is represented at the industry body, the Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association (BGMEA). 
o    China and wider region: ETI has an office in Hong Kong for our work in China and the wider region. With the ILO SCORE Programme, we started working to improve the productivity, competitiveness and sustainability of 17 small and medium-sized enterprises supplying eight ETI members through workplace training and in-house consultancy. 
o    India: in collaboration with a local Indian not-for-profit CSR agency, we continue to raise business and civil society awareness of the business and human rights agenda. Working with leading Indian business schools, we show how businesses have sought to respect human rights in the local context. As the only large-scale workers’ rights project working directly within spinning mills and garment factories in southern India, our Tamil Nadu Multi Stakeholder Initiative (TNMS) seeks to address the working conditions of young women workers. 
o    Myanmar: ETI is investigating the potential for establishing a local Burmese platform in partnership with our sister organisation, the Danish Ethical Trading Initiative. 
o    Pakistan: in partnership with a local labour rights organisation we are building a multi-stakeholder initiative and increasing awareness and understanding of local businesses on human rights due diligence and ethical trade. 
o    Spain: Human Rights Due Diligence analysis on working conditions in the agricultural sector in Southern Spain for the benefit of ETI’s supermarket members. 
o    Thailand: ETI engages in dialogue with the Thai government, the ILO, industry associations, leading Thai companies, local unions and NGOs to improve workers’ conditions, particularly in the seafood industry.  
o    Turkey: bringing together key stakeholders within the garment industry to improve working conditions, advocate for decent work and reduce the risk of modern slavery, particularly for Syrian refugees. 
o    UK: a local programme focused on improving conditions for workers in  garment factories and increasing their representation and access to remedy.  

2.    We regularly commission new Research and publish guidance, reports on various ethical trade issues. The most recent ones include:  
o    Report “Corporate leadership on modern slavery”; 
o    Guide to buying responsibly; 
o    Human rights due diligence framework; 
o    Base code guidance: Modern slavery; 
o    Base code guidance: child labour; 
o    Base code guidance: working hours;  
o    Base code guidance: Living wages; 
o    Ethical Trade and the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs); 
o    Ethical procurement for health workbook; 
o    Integrating ethical trade principles in core business practice;  
o    Due diligence in agricultural supply chains: counter-acting exploitation of migrant workers in Italian tomato production; 

3.    Advocacy:  
o    Engagement with Government institutions and bodies in UK to build support for improved legislative and practical application of initiatives to prevent modern slavery in national and global supply chains and to protect workers’ rights;  
o    Engagement with Department for International Development on Alliance 8.7, a global partnership committed to take immediate and effective measures to eradicate forced labour, modern slavery, human trafficking and child labour, in accordance with Target 8.7 of the UN Agenda 2030 for Sustainable Development Goals; 
o    ETI is involved in an ongoing Organisation for Security Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) project to encourage member states to strengthen their legislation on modern slavery transparency, labour market protection and public procurement procedures. 
